# CSS Style Guide

*This rule automatically attaches when working with CSS files.*

## Organization

- **Avoid inline styles** - Use external CSS files or `<style>` blocks
- Organize CSS by component, page, or feature
- Use CSS variables for consistent values (colors, spacing, fonts)
- Follow a consistent methodology (BEM, SMACSS, OOCSS, etc.)

## Naming Conventions

- Use consistent naming (BEM recommended: `.block__element--modifier`)
- Use kebab-case for class names
- Use descriptive, semantic class names
- Avoid generic names like `.box`, `.container` (be more specific)

## CSS Variables

Define and use CSS variables for consistency:

```css
:root {
  --primary-color: #007bff;
  --secondary-color: #6c757d;
  --font-family: 'Inter', sans-serif;
  --spacing-unit: 1rem;
}

.button {
  background-color: var(--primary-color);
  font-family: var(--font-family);
  padding: var(--spacing-unit);
}
```

## Font Management

- Define fonts in CSS, not inline
- Use a single primary font family
- Define font stack in `:root` or main CSS file
- Use consistent font sizes (use rem/em, not px for scalability)

## Responsive Design

- Use mobile-first approach
- Use consistent breakpoints
- Test on multiple screen sizes
- Use relative units (rem, em, %) when possible

## Specificity and Conflicts

- Avoid overly specific selectors
- Don't use `!important` unless absolutely necessary
- Organize CSS to prevent conflicts
- Use CSS modules or scoped styles when possible

## Example Structure

```css
/* Variables */
:root {
  --primary-color: #007bff;
  --font-family: 'Inter', sans-serif;
}

/* Base styles */
body {
  font-family: var(--font-family);
}

/* Component styles */
.button {
  /* ... */
}

.button--primary {
  /* ... */
}

/* Utility classes */
.text-center {
  text-align: center;
}
```

